As for the Markov chain notes, and the comparison of definition 4.29 and
definition 2.2.1 in RMT, I think there are two differences, one small
technical one and one conceptual one. I followed more the logic of
Billingsley but I believe one can proceed in both ways, because the
Markov chain is so simple that technical details wash out, and the
conceptual issue can in the end be interpreted more as a language issue.

1. The technical difference is that invariant sets can include states
that have zero probability under the invariant measure. This does not
really matter for anything for practical purposes.

2. The conceptual difference is that ergodicity in Billingsley is
defined on measure-preserving maps, so stationarity is imposed from the
onset. Similarly, your theorems 2.E.1 and 2.E.3 assume stationary Markov
chains. The notion of absorbing sets is, at least in my mind, more
related to transition dynamics. However, every absorbing subset from
definition 2.2.1 will be an invariant set, but invariant sets are also
unions of absorbing subsets (plus they can also include states that have
measure zero under the stationary measure). This required including the
mention to the smallest invariant set in proposition 4.30. With a deeper
definition of a conditional expectation, one could get away with a
statement that the right-hand side of the proposition 4.30 is the
conditional expectation conditional on the sigma-algebra generated by
invariant sets, but without that definition at hand, I needed to write
around a bit.

In any case, it is clear from the above discussion that one can proceed
with the notion of absorbing subsets, and the results will hold.
